FT  17 DEC 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Today The Essential History Of Europe is about the French. Let's hope the
programme obscures the fact that the Italians taught them to cook, and
overlooks the Second World War. French TV is another sore point, as is the
erosion of the French language by English. Oh, and the subject of wine is
best avoided: French wines now lose so often against the Australians in
blind tastings that the French are starting to sulk. Kinder to ignore pop
music and modern drama, too, and although you can hardly disregard their
racism remember that it is only a bit more virulent than that in Germany and
Britain. Otherwise they are marvellous people (8.00 BBC2). BBC2's Video
Diaries series has been very mixed. Some have been compelling, others
scarcely worth watching. Today's was made by Elhanan Oppenheim who lives in
the occupied West Bank. For That Was This Week That Was (9.00 ITV) the
poacher/presenter has turned gamekeeper. After 36 years, the programme ends
with a retrospective which attempts to discover what the programme did, why
it got into trouble with the government, and what may replace it.
