<TEXT>
BACKERS OF the campaign to secure vital submarine work for Plymouth's
Devonport dockyard yesterday withdrew allegations that details of a dock
project were leaked from the Ministry of Defence to the rival yard at Rosyth
in Fife, David White writes.
Mr Gary Streeter, Conservative MP for Plymouth Sutton, said he accepted the
ministry's assurances that no leak had taken place.
Mr Mike Leece, managing director of Devonport Management, the yard's
operator, said he had received similar assurances in writing from consulting
engineers on the rival projects, on which several thousand jobs are at
stake.
He added: 'We were suspicious that anyone could put forward a scheme very
similar to ours without a leak taking place.'
The two yards are competing for the contract to refit the UK's latest
Trident ballistic-missile submarines, which cannot be accommodated in
existing dock facilities.
Both consider the contract vital to their survival.
