<DATE>921217
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / Lords back MMC over bus combine
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT attempts to reduce takeover activity and increase competition in
the bus industry received unexpected support yesterday when the Monopolies
and Mergers Commission won its final appeal in the Sheffield bus mergers
case.
Five law lords ruled unanimously that the commission had the power to
investigate local bus company mergers under the terms of the 1973 Fair
Trading Act. They restored a 1990 MMC recommendation that South Yorkshire
Transport (SYT) should sell four rival bus companies it acquired in 1989.
The decision will be a severe blow to private-sector bus companies hoping to
build up their strength through acquisitions.
Mr Richard Boardman, the Leeds lawyer who handled the case for SYT, said the
decision 'opened the floodgates for thousands of other investigations' into
small local mergers.
The commission's report, which was accepted by Mr Peter Lilley, then trade
and industry secretary, recommended that SYT should sell Sheffield and
District Transport, Sheafline (PSV), Michael Groves and SUT on the ground
that each merger might be expected to operate against the public interest.
As a result of the acquisitions, SYT's share of bus miles in Sheffield
increased to the point at which the commission said competition to SYT in
Sheffield had, in effect, ceased.
It said each acquisition could result in higher fares as well as lower
standards, declining quality and frequency of service and less choice.
The commission's decision was challenged by SYT on the ground that the
commission had no jurisdiction to investigate the acquisitions because they
did not affect a 'substantial part of the UK' within the context of the
market-share test set out in the 1973 act.
In March last year, the High Court overturned the commission's
recommendation that the mergers should be reversed.
It said the area of operation examined by the commission was not a
'substantial part of the UK' according to the meaning of the 1973 act. That
decision was upheld by the Appeal Court in November last year.
But the law lords said that where the task was to interpret an enabling
provision, intended to confer on the commission the power to investigate
mergers believed to be against the public interest, the court should lean
against an interpretation that would severely limit the commission's
jurisdiction.
In deciding whether a merger affected 'a substantial part of the UK' and
therefore qualified for investigation, the commission had to be satisfied
that the 'part' was 'of such size, character and importance as to make it
worth consideration for the purposes of the act'.
The law lords ruled that it could not be said that the commission had
misapplied that test in the present case. It therefore had power to
investigate the acquisitions.
The commission said yesterday: 'We are very gratified by the result.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-1614</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLQCFACIFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921217
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / Banks reject wide ombudsman role
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BANKS yesterday publicly rejected the idea of extending the banking
ombudsman scheme to cover small business complaints.
The idea is being discussed in meetings this week between Mr Norman Lamont,
the chancellor, and senior bankers.
Sir Nicholas Goodison, president of the British Bankers' Association, said
it would be 'impractical' to extend the scheme's terms of reference.
'If you started changing the terms, you would end up with a muddle,' he
said.
Sir Nicholas said incorporated businesses had redress against banks through
the courts.
The ombudsman would not be equipped to 'second guess' banks' commercial
decisions, such as what rate of interest to charge on loans.
He said he could not disclose the topics of discussion between Mr Lamont and
the chairmen and chief executives of banks this week.
The chancellor is, however, thought to have raised the idea of extending the
scheme.
Mr Lamont yesterday met Sir Nicholas, Mr Andrew Buxton, the chief executive
of Barclays Bank, and Mr Derek Wanless, chief executive of National
Westminster Bank.
The chancellor has been urging banks to pass on base rate cuts to borrowers.
National Westminster Bank said Mr Wanless told the chancellor the vast
majority of allegations about banks and small business were 'unsubstantiated
and misplaced'. The bank had passed on all base rate cuts in full . Two
years ago the government rejected suggestions by the Jack Committee on
banking services that small businesses should be brought within the scope of
the banking ombudsman scheme. The scheme is funded and supported by banks.
Separately, Sir Jeremy Morse, chairman of Lloyds Bank, last night criticised
both the government and the press for their role in encouraging what he
called 'the biggest wave of anti-bank sentiment in Britain since the 1930s'.
Sir Jeremy, making his presidential address to the Chartered Institute of
Bankers in London, said the government had been 'happy to find someone else
to share the blame for the hardships in the economy'.
Banks faced further criticism from the Consumers' Association, however. It
said high street banks had been 'unacceptably slow' in implementing the
banking code of practice and had made 'parsimonious' interpretations of it.
Ms Jean Eaglesham said that 'honourable exceptions apart', banks had
implemented the code in a 'slow, half-hearted, grudging' way and favoured
their own interests over customers when there was a clash.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-1615</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CLQCFACHFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921217
