<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Major and Bush to debate Serbia
plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEW MEASURES to tighten sanctions against Serbia in response to the
deteriorating situation in Bosnia are expected to be finalised this weekend
at talks between Mr John Major and President George Bush.
British officials said yesterday that the two leaders, who meet in the US at
the end of a week of international meetings on Bosnia, may also settle the
terms of the new UN resolution designed to enforce the no-fly zone over the
former Yugoslav province.
Mr Major remains more cautious than his US counterpart about the possibility
of military action against Serbian aircraft violating the zone. Ministers
repeated yesterday their concerns that such action would risk retaliation
against British ground forces and might wreck the humanitarian effort.
The officials said a compromise was emerging between London and Washington
on a package combining tougher sanctions and a new UN resolution. They
pointed out that the passage of such a resolution, expected next week, would
not automatically imply that intruding aircraft would be shot down.
Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary, suggested that Serbia be treated as
an international pariah, with existing sanctions supplemented by cuts in
telephone links and diplomatic contacts, possibly the sealing of borders.
Mr Major will spend two days with Mr Bush in Camp David at the weekend after
an EC-US summit in Washington on Friday. The prime minister will be
accompanied at the summit by Mr Jacques Delors, the European Commission
president, who will also join him later today for an EC-Canada summit in
Ottawa.
Both of the EC meetings will be dominated by the slow progress of the Gatt
talks in Geneva, where last month's breakthrough on US-EC farm trade has
failed to unravel all the disputes holding up completion of the Uruguay
Round.
Mr Major will press the outgoing administration to review its decision to
impose countervailing duties on EC steel imports. He will also sound out the
possibility of a compromise on the disputes over industrial tariffs that are
holding up progress in Geneva.
Baroness Thatcher last night called for air strikes against Serbian
artillery, tanks and supply lines if they do not withdraw their troops from
Sarajevo and other besieged Bosnian towns.
The former prime minister said in The European newspaper that by stating in
public repeatedly that 'we will not intervene militarily' the west had to
some extent not been neutrals but 'more like accomplices'.
</TEXT>
