<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: MP cautious over sale of
Parcelforce
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT is running into fresh difficulties in its attempts to
privatise Parcelforce because it may not be able to transfer any surplus in
the parcel deliverer's pension fund to a private-sector buyer, a Labour MP
will tell the Commons today.
Mr Peter Hain, Labour MP for Neath, will use a debate on the future of
postal services in rural areas to argue that present trust deeds would
prevent such a transfer - a contention that is believed to be supported by
professional advice in the hands of the Post Office, Parcelforce's current
owner.
Mr Hain will put the current level of surplus in the Post Office's pension
fund, accumulated over four years, at Pounds 311m and will estimate that
Parcelforce's share of this could amount to some Pounds 20m.
He is also expected to return to the question of Parcelforce's exemption
from value added tax, which it is expected to lose once it ceases to be part
of the Post Office. Parcelforce has a 34 per cent share - the largest in the
market - of ordinary parcel deliveries but only 2 per cent of the premium
'next-day' market.
Earlier this week it was disclosed that the division had cut its first-half
losses from Pounds 27m to Pounds 21m. Sir Bryan Nicholson, Post Office
chairman, said Parcelforce hoped to break even by the end of its financial
year.
Government moves to strengthen the voice of passengers in the regions after
rail privatisation were endorsed by Mr Roger Freeman, transport minister,
last night.
'The current system of consumer representation by the consultative
committees works well and we are committed to ensuring that none of the
benefits are lost,' he said.
</TEXT>
