<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Labour leaders pressed on Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PRESSURE ON the Labour leadership to take a more overtly pro-Europe stance
came last night from 85 of the party's MPs who urged 'the rapid completion'
of the Maastricht treaty's ratification.
The move by senior figures, including Mr Neil Kinnock, the former leader,
will increase the pressure on Mr John Smith, his successor, not to take any
action that would block or hinder the treaty's progress when it returns to
the Commons next year. It was designed to counter the tactics of a
significant minority of anti-Maastricht Labour MPs and other Labour
Euro-sceptics. Other signatories of the pro-Maastricht 'early day motion',
included Mr Roy Hattersley, former deputy leader, Mr Gerald Kaufman, former
shadow foreign secretary, and Mr Peter Mandelson, the party's former
communications director who is now MP for Hartlepool.
The carefully worded motion notes how the European socialist leaders'
meeting in Edinburgh last weekend backed 'the rapid completion of the
ratification of the Maastricht treaty and its implementation'.
That, the motion says, is 'in accordance' with Labour policy and it calls on
the government to endorse the social chapter in the treaty, 'so that passage
of the European Communities (Amendment) Bill can receive the wholehearted
support of both sides of the House (of Commons) at the earliest
opportunity'.
Meanwhile, the party's post-election revamp took a further step forward
yesterday when the ruling national executive agreed to cut headquarters
spending by a third and to set up an independent 'social justice
commission'.
Mr Smith will announce today the membership of the Social Justice
Commission, dubbed the 'new Beveridge', which will report on Britain's tax
and benefit system. It comes as Mr Smith received a warning from Mr
Hattersley that Labour had to develop policies to excite the electorate  -
and not depend on the government's continuing misfortune.
The commission will be chaired by Sir Gordon Borrie, former director-general
of fair trading, and run by the left-leaning Institute for Public Policy
Research. Not all its members will be Labour supporters.
The national executive committee discussed the commission only briefly
yesterday but spent much of a five-hour meeting debating spending cuts
forced by the fall in party membership and in donations from unions.
A report by the party's finance committee was not formally approved but a
Labour official said the NEC had agreed the thrust of its recommendations:
that spending on day-to-day running of the party will have to be cut by 30
per cent in 1993 to about Pounds 8m. Numbers employed at Labour's
headquarters will fall from a peak of 120 to 90. Many of the jobs have
already gone since the general election but the NEC wants a review of the
party's management structure and has not ruled out compulsory redundancies.
There are also to be consultations on proposals to cut the number of Labour
party regions in England from nine to either six or seven.
Meanwhile, Mr Hattersley said Labour should stand by its commitment to
creating a more equal society. It should not shy away from advocating an
increase in income tax for those with above-average earnings, he said. While
distancing himself from recent criticism within the party of Mr Smith, Mr
Hattersley said the time had come to open a second front. He warned that
Labour would not win the next election by relying on a combination of
dissatisfaction with the Tories, the class-interest of the lower income
groups and support for the party's new-found political responsibility.
</TEXT>
