FT  17 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: IRA strikes again
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLICE sealed off a large area of London's West End yesterday after two
small bombs injured three people, Bethan Hutton writes.
The first bomb, placed in third-floor lavatories at the John Lewis
Partnership department store in Oxford Street, exploded about half an hour
after vaguely worded warnings had been telephoned to news organisations by
callers claiming to be from the IRA. The second bomb, in a litter bin in
Cavendish Square, directly behind John Lewis, went off 10 minutes later as
staff and customers were being evacuated.
The three casualties were taken to hospital with minor injuries, together
with a fourth, a man who suffered an asthma attack after the explosions.
Commander David Tucker, head of Scotland Yard's anti-terrorist branch, said
the attack was part of the 'obscene game' the IRA wished to play with the
police.
'The pattern is there: imprecise messages not indicating inside the store or
outside the store, and impossible time scales for the police to clear the
area.'
Mr Tucker said both bombs appeared to be small, but it was 'miraculous' that
there had not been more injuries.
Oxford Street was closed for several hours. Damage to the John Lewis
building was limited and the store reopened later.
</TEXT>
