<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / Recession forces new rise in PSBR
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT finances continued to show the scars of recession last month as
the public-sector borrowing requirement jumped to Pounds 2.18bn from Pounds
1.66bn in October and only Pounds 293m in November last year.
The Central Statistical Office said the deficit for the first eight months
of the financial year amounted to Pounds 22.3bn compared with Pounds 9bn in
the same period of 1991-92 and the latest official forecast of Pounds 37bn
for the total 1992-93 PSBR, announced in last month's Autumn Statement.
November's deterioration in the UK's finances was slightly less than the
consensus forecast on financial markets, where the figures had little impact
because the government has overfunded its borrowing requirement so far this
year. Looking ahead, however, Mr Michael Saunders, UK economist of Salomon
Brothers International in London, warned that a further worsening of the
PSBR might lead to a tax-raising spring budget.
Privatisation proceeds in November were close to zero for the second month
running. Over the eight months to November, public borrowing, excluding
privatisation receipts, was Pounds 27.1bn, nearly twice the Pounds 14.1bn of
the same period of 1991.
</TEXT>
