<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / Surveyors report housing 'spring'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ROYAL Institution of Chartered Surveyors today reports what may be 'the
first sign of spring flowers' for the housing market, with increased
activity in late November continuing - against the seasonal norm - into
December.
Its survey of market conditions in England and Wales for the quarter to the
end of November based on chartered surveyors who operate as estate agents
says the trend may herald a return of confidence next year.
Mr Peter Miller, the institution's residential-property spokesman, says: 'We
now have the foundations on which, given some good economic news on output
or retail sales, the recovery can be built.'
Lending rates, the survey says, are now at their lowest for many years; the
ratio between house prices and earnings is at its most favourable for at
least 10 years; there is a big supply of keenly priced houses; and pent-up
demand from first-time buyers is very high and 'just waiting' for improved
confidence. Mr Miller says: 'If, as we expect, the first six months of 1993
witness increased levels of activity, underlying demand could be unleashed
and actually outstrip supply, leading to price rises at the bottom end of
the market. Increased demand will then move slowly up the housing ladder.'
In spite of the survey's guarded optimism, it discloses the depths to which
the housing market has sunk this year. The 150 agents who responded sold an
average of just 19 properties in the past three months compared with an
average of 159 secondhand houses and flats for which direct instructions
were received.
The survey also shows sharp contrasts on the effects of interest rate cuts.
A Northampton agent said November saw a flurry of activity as a result of
rate cuts and the belief that the bottom of the market might have been
reached. In Bishop Auckland, Co Durham, however, there were few signs of the
market moving.
Housing Market, RICS, 12 Great George St, Parliament Sq, London SW1P 3AD.
Free.
</TEXT>
