<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / Sunday ruling fails to produce open-and-shut case: The
implications of the European Court decision
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Court ruling on Sunday trading was unexpectedly clear, but did
little to end the confusion surrounding the issue.
The EC Court of Justice ruled Sunday trading laws in England and Wales did
not clash with European trade laws and were enforceable.
The ruling has intensified calls for a review of the current laws.
'It's a historical decision rather than one of historic significance,' said
Mr Nigel Whittaker, corporate affairs director of Kingfisher retail group,
which includes B&amp;Q, Woolworth and Comet. 'It leaves the way clear for the
Home Office to press ahead with new legislation.'
The court was not ruling simply on the legality or otherwise of shops'
opening on Sundays. Rather, it was asked to guide the English courts in
interpreting an apparent clash between the Shops Act of 1950, which is
supposed to regulate Sunday trading in England and Wales, and Article 30 of
the Treaty of Rome, which forbids any barrier to trade between member
countries.
Retailers said their turnover was reduced if they did not open on Sunday,
meaning they needed to import fewer goods from Europe - a form of trade
barrier. The counter-argument from the anti Sunday-trade lobby was that the
aim of the Shops Act, to protect workers, justified any breach of trade
laws.
The European Court had to decide whether the Shops Act was 'proportionate',
in other words whether its effect on trade was no more than necessary to
achieve its objective of worker protection.
Its decision was clear-cut: 'Article 30 of the Treaty is to be interpreted
as meaning that the prohibition which it lays down does not apply to
national legislation prohibiting retailers from opening their premises on
Sundays.'
The ruling must now go to the Lords for ratification.
But the Home Office indicated that it was now up to councils to decide
whether to prosecute shops opening on Sundays, and several said they would
do so. Others are thought unlikely to spend time and money trying to enforce
what is seen is a dying law.
The ruling is not the end of the story.
The existing legislation is clearly doomed, and new proposals will be put to
parliament.
The first will be the private member's bill sponsored by Mr Ray Powell,
Labour MP for Ogmore, due to be debated on January 22.
The bill aims to rationalise the Shops Act, taking into account the
retailing needs of the 1990s, and provide adequate protection for Sunday
workers.
It is based on the proposals of Keep Sunday Special, the campaign group,
which would permit the opening of shops in four categories: recreation,
emergencies, social and travel - hence the acronym Rest - at council
discretion.
The recreation category includes sports centres, historic buildings,
newsagents, garden centres and florists. The emergency category covers
chemists and small food shops, while the social category includes
restaurants, take-aways, pubs and off licences. The travel section would
cover petrol stations, motor spares shops and motorway service stations.
Ministers are unlikely to force Tory backbenchers to attend and vote against
the bill, so its progress will depend on Mr Powell's skills as a whip (he is
a senior member of the Labour whips' office) and on backbench opposition to
it.
Even assuming it is allowed to proceed in January, there is practically no
prospect that it will become law. Discussion on backbench bills cannot be
guillotined, and time available for them is very limited. So the realistic
route for a change in the law is government legislation.
The Conservatives promised in their last two manifestos to reform Sunday
trading laws, and Mr Kenneth Clarke, home secretary, told parliament in
November that he planned to present a so-called 'options' bill.
That would give MPs the chance to choose between complete deregulation of
Sunday opening (Mr Clarke's favoured option but considered unlikely to gain
widespread support); the KSS/Rest proposals; and partial deregulation as
proposed by the Shopping Hours Reform Council.
The reform council, whose proposals are supported by retail groups including
J. Sainsbury and Kingfisher, wants all shops to be allowed to open for all
or part of the day, depending on their size. Shops below 3,000 sq ft would
face no restriction, but larger shops would be allowed to open for only
limited hours.
The council also wants legislation to include protection for shop workers,
outlawing any attempts to force workers to work on Sundays or discrimination
against those who refuse.
Premium wages should also be paid for Sunday working.
Mr Clarke's desire to press ahead with legislation on Sunday trading is not
in doubt. More in question is the enthusiasm of Mr Tony Newton, the leader
of the Commons, for introducing a bill that would be time-consuming and
divisive. The business managers say that the legislative programme is
already full of controversial measures, not least the Maastricht bill and
the legislation to privatise British Rail.
So Mr Clarke may lose his battle for a bill to clear up the confusion before
next Christmas.
Even if he wins it, the passage of the legislation will be far from a
formality. Although ministers are relaxed enough about the extent of
deregulation to include three different options, they have no intention of
giving in on the question of employee protection.
The campaign to get premium wages for shop employees who choose to work on
Sundays and give future as well as existing shop workers the right not to
work on Sundays unites both the KSS and the reform council.
For a Tory administration that sees as one of its lasting achievements of
the 1980s as the removal of government intervention from industrial
relations, the prospect of reintroducing that in the form of wage regulation
might well prove unacceptable.
But Labour MPs are unlikely to refuse the invitation to join in defeating
the government over workers' rights.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
