<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / Retailers stick to seasonal plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RETAILERS pledged yesterday to press ahead with plans to open this Sunday -
the last before Christmas - although some said they would take legal advice
on continuing Sunday trading in the new year.
Early legislation on Sunday trading was demanded by shops and councils on
both sides of the debate.
'The European Court ruling adds urgency to the home secretary to reform this
unworkable and unpopular law,' Mr Ron Trenter, chairman of Texas Homecare,
the DIY chain, said. 'It should now be given parliamentary priority.'
Stores and local authorities said the European Court ruling could not be
seen as not a final judgment on the issue, as a House of Lords ruling is
pending. 'The case has been somewhat overtaken by political events. Only two
weeks ago the home secretary announced the funeral arrangements for the
Shops Act 1950,' Mr David Ramsden, retail services controller of B&amp;Q, the
DIY chain, said.
Mr David Quarmby, joint managing director of J. Sainsbury, the UK's biggest
food retailer, said: 'Our plans are in place to open this Sunday and we do
intend to. We have had only four days' notice and our customers and staff
are expecting us to open.'
He said the company would take advice from its lawyers about Sunday trading
in the future.
Tesco, the supermarket group, said its stores also would open next Sunday.
'The company feels it would be quite wrong to change its arrangements and
disappoint its 1 1/2 m Sunday shoppers. It would also be unfair to deprive
the 18,000 Tesco staff who work on Sundays of an income they are counting on
just before Christmas.'
The John Lewis Partnership, one of the retailers to hold out against Sunday
opening, said the European ruling made clear that the Shops Act 1950 still
stood. John Lewis said that Waitrose, its supermarket chain, was losing
Pounds 1m a week by abiding by the law. The partnership also wants
parliament to enact new legislation as early as possible.
Some councils, which took rigorous legal action against stores trading on
Sundays, said they did not plan to apply for injunctions until after the
House of Lords ruled on the issue.
Stoke-on-Trent City Council, which together with Norwich council has been
involved in a protracted legal battle with B&amp;Q over Sunday opening, said the
ruling was a 'complete vindication' of the city's stance.
But Mr Paul Hodgson, the assistant city secretary, said: 'Now we have to
wait for the House of Lords to rule on the matter.'
Kirklees council in West Yorkshire rejected using injunctions in the
immediate future, but said its policy of responding to complaints from the
public would continue, although prosecution after a complaint, imposing only
small fines, was less of a deterrent than an injunction that forced a store
to remain closed.
