   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US OPPONENTS of the North American Free Trade Agreement, due to be signed in
Washington today, are about to launch an advertising campaign against it.
Critics of the US-Canada-Mexico deal say it is 'a wrecking ball' aimed at
the US economy and a potential environmental disaster.
The Mexican government wants Nafta passed as soon as possible: it expects a
current deficit of Dollars 20bn this year and sees it as essential to
attract foreign capital.
The Economic Strategy Institute in Washington yesterday recommended
far-reaching changes in the agreement. It wants US textile quotas from other
exporting nations shifted to Mexico in order to prevent job losses in the US
industry.
