FT  17 DEC 92 / Israel to bail out IMI
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE ISRAELI government yesterday agreed to bail out the financially stricken
Israel Military Industries in an attempt to keep afloat one of the mainstays
of the country's big state-owned defence industry, which has been hard hit
by falling world demand for military products.
The cabinet voted to back a recovery plan for IMI - best known as the maker
of the Uzi sub-machine gun - which includes an injection of Shk750m (Pounds
190m) in government funds and a 2,500 cut in the present 7,500-strong
workforce. Previously, the government had pumped Shk250m into IMI to staunch
losses which approached Dollars 250m (Pounds 164m) last year on sales which
fell 20 per cent to Dollars 520m.
Aside from IMI, the government is also being asked by Israel Aircraft
Industries, the country's biggest company, for more than Dollars 150m in
emergency aid to help it cope with falling sales.
