FT  17 DEC 92 / UN soldiers captured in Cambodia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VICTOR MALLET
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BANGKOK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KHMER ROUGE guerrillas have seized 21 United Nations peacekeepers in central
Cambodia in the second such incident this month, the UN Transitional
Authority in Cambodia said last night.
'We don't think they are in any kind of danger and we're confident they will
be released shortly,' Mr Eric Falt, the Untac spokesman, said in the
capital, Phnom Penh.
The captives, still held last night in Kompong Thom province, include 15
Indonesian soldiers, four military observers - from the US, China, France
and Senegal - and two Cambodian interpreters.
On December 1, a Khmer Rouge guerrilla unit in the same province held six
military observers for three days after they penetrated Khmer Rouge
territory by driving up a river in inflatable boats. They were released
unharmed.
The Khmer Rouge was one of four Cambodian factions to sign a peace accord in
Paris last year which paved the way for the UN's Dollars 2bn (Pounds 1.3bn)
peacekeeping operation, but it has repeatedly flouted the accord.
