<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / Industrial protests increase in Poland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INDUSTRIAL PROTEST grew in Poland yesterday as more than half the country's
coal miners went on strike and railway workers in Silesia, the country's
industrial heartland, threatened to disrupt transport of freight, writes
Christopher Bobinski in Warsaw.
Steel unions meet today to consider whether to join the protests, which aim
to force the government to address the region's industrial restructuring
needs. The strikers, led by Solidarity and supported by other local unions,
are demanding that energy price rises this year and next be fully
compensated with wage increases.
The region accounts for 70 per cent of Poland's rail freight traffic and
strike leaders see selected stoppages as a means of putting pressure on the
government. But pithead coal stocks and power station reserves are high,
giving the government a temporary advantage.
It has yet to respond to the strikers' demands, Solidarity said yesterday.
The strikes started on Monday with a two-hour national token stoppage by
Solidarity in support of the wage rises. By yesterday afternoon 45 of
Poland's 70 coal mines had stopped, as the stoppages spread spontaneously.
Coal miners won significant pay increases after intermittent strikes in the
summer and their wages this year have risen in real terms by 2 per cent
against a 5 per cent real incomes drop throughout manufacturing industry.
Forecasts see real wages staying at this year's levels in 1993.
</TEXT>
