<HEADLINE>
FT  17 DEC 92 / Ford of Europe to shed 10,000 jobs next year: UK and Germany
worst hit - Renault and VW to cut workforces
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE and CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD, the US carmaker, is to reduce the workforce of its European automotive
operations by 11 per cent, cutting more than 10,000 jobs by the end of 1993
in a further heavy blow to employment in the European motor industry.
The sharpest reductions will be in the UK, where the workforce has already
been more than halved in the last decade, and in Germany. They are part of
restructuring moves aimed at staunching Ford of Europe's mounting losses.
The company said in Detroit last night it would take a one-time Dollars 419m
(Pounds 266m) after-tax charge as a result of the European job cuts.
Mr Harold Poling, Ford group chairman, said this charge and additional
one-off charges relating to US accounting changes would result in a net loss
from worldwide operations for the whole of 1992. Additional accounting
charges in line with those of other big US companies include a Dollars 440m
write-off related to 1992 and a separate Pounds 7.5bn charge.
Car and truckmakers in Europe are under increasing pressure from declining
sales, overcapacity and intensifying competition from Japanese carmakers.
Yesterday, Renault Vehicules Industriels, the loss-making French commercial
vehicle maker, said it planned to cut its workforce and heavy job losses are
expected at Volkswagen. In contrast, Toyota, the leading Japanese car
producer, opened its first European car plant in the UK at Burnaston, near
Derby.
Ford said it planned to reduce the workforce of its European automotive
operations, excluding Jaguar, to 83,000 by the end of 1993 from the present
level of 93,000. The workforce has already been cut by 19 per cent from
115,000 in 1990.
About 80 per cent of the latest job cuts will be made in the UK and Germany,
with each operation equally affected. The salaried workforce in Europe will
be reduced by 14.5 per cent from 17,550 to 15,000 by mid-1993, while the
hourly-paid workforce will be reduced from 75,200 to 68,000 by the end of
1993.
Some 1,180 hourly-paid jobs in the UK and 1,500 in Germany are to be
eliminated by April as a result of cuts in production capacity, with the
rest to go through improved efficiency measures by the end of 1993.
About 1,200 salaried jobs are to be cut in the UK, mainly at Ford's Dunton
engineering operations and the Warley headquarters, both in Essex. A further
1,000 salaried jobs in the UK have already been eliminated by using excess
volunteers to the earlier redundancy programme launched in September. A
further 1,350 salaried jobs will be cut in Germany, mainly in Cologne.
Responding to the UK job losses Mr Jimmy Airlie, chief Ford negotiator and
executive council member of the AEEU electrical and engineering union, said:
'Three months ago, Ford announced compulsory redundancies and said they were
cutting lay-off pay from 100 per cent of basic to 60 per cent. Today there
are no compulsory redundancies and they have reinstated lay-off pay in
full.'
Mr Jack Adams, deputy general secretary of the TGWU general union, said: 'If
one Ford worker is made compulsorily redundant next year, we shall ballot
our members with a recommendation for industrial action.' Ford's UK
workforce has already fallen from a peak of 80,000 in early 1980 to 33,000
by the end of this year, an average reduction of more than 3,600 a year.
With new car sales forecast to decline further next year Ford is cutting
production capacity sharply in the UK and Germany. Capacity is being
increased at Genk in Belgium for production of a new model, while Valencia
in Spain, Ford's most cost-effective plant in Europe, largely escapes the
cuts.
Fiesta output at Dagenham in the UK will be reduced by 18 per cent to 740 a
day and production of Fiestas and Scorpios at Cologne will be cut by 23 per
cent to 1,020 cars a day. Capacity will also be reduced at Halewood in the
UK and Saarlouis in Germany.
Further cuts in the workforce will follow in later years as a result of
other measures announced yesterday.
Mr Bill Fike, president of Ford of Europe, said the company would
concentrate on the design, manufacture and sale of cars and light commercial
vehicles.
Ford's European operations have collapsed into loss in the second half of
this year 1992 after struggling back into profit in the first six months.
from record losses last year. The European automotive operations suffered a
third quarter loss of Dollars 479m (Pounds 304m). in the third quarter.
In yesterday's other developments:
Volkswagen, the leader of the west European car market, said it had fallen
into loss in the last quarter of this year. VW is expected shortly to
announce further restructuring, including heavy job cuts. Renault Vehicules
Industriels said it was planning to cut 1,348 jobs, or 8 per cent of its
workforce, in France.
