<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / Spastics Society criticises Tecs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Spastics Society yesterday criticised the standard of training provided
to disabled people by the Training and Enterprise Councils.
A report based on a survey of 138 organisations involved with disabled
people said most Tecs had failed in their responsibility to ensure suitable
high-quality training for disabled people.
Mr Brian Lamb, the society's head of campaigns, said: 'Tecs have not met the
training needs of disabled people and the gap between the rhetoric of what
was supposed to be on offer and the reality is enormous.'
Tecs, in their contracts with government, have to take account of the
training requirements of 'special needs' clients. The society criticised the
present funding regime for failing to recognise the extra costs that may be
involved in training a disabled person.
Cuts in provision had had a disproportionate effect on disabled people and
fundamentally undermined the Tecs' abilities to carry out government
policies aimed at targeted groups, the society said.
Wasted Opportunities, Spastics Society, 12 Park Crescent, London W1N 4EQ.
Pounds 4.95.
