<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / World Trade News: Vodafone moves into Australia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AUSTRALIA has awarded an operator's licence for a mobile telephone network
to a group owned by Vodafone of the UK. Called Arena GSM, it becomes the
third licence-holder for Australia, one of the world's fastest growing
markets.
Arena GSM is paying ADollars 140m for the licence and intends to invest
another ADollars 400m in the project. It beat off three other shortlisted
companies: Singapore Telecom and local operators Matrix Telecommunications
and Voxson.
The new service is scheduled to start by next October and must be available
to 80 per cent of the population by the end of 1996, according to the terms
of the licence.
The latter also requires Australian interests to control more than half of
Arena GSM by 2003. Arena GSM will be competing against existing
licence-holders, Optus Communications and the state-owned Australian and
Overseas Telecommunications Corporation.
The infrastructure for the new network is likely to be supplied either by
Ericsson or Sweden or Finland's Nokia.
Vodafone - see Lex
