<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / Disputes over employees' terms threaten council tendering
plans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEGAL confusion is threatening the government's plans to extend competitive
tendering in local government, according to companies and councils involved.
The problem concerns the status of employees' terms and conditions when
contracts change hands.
At least two local authorities have had their tendering plans thrown into
disarray in the past week by disputes over the law on the transfer of
'undertakings' - agreements covering staff terms and conditions.
Private contractor Initial Cleaning Services said last night that the
uncertainty could 'completely destroy the government's marketing, testing
and competitive tendering programme, unless it is resolved soon'.
Mr Rodney Brooke, secretary of the Labour-run Association of Metropolitan
Authorities, said: 'Local councils are between the devil and the deep blue
sea. If they seek to transfer undertakings, they risk government penalties;
if they don't, they risk being sued by their employees.'
The Institute of Directors said it was 'deeply concerned about the current
confusion'. It wants the government not only to clarify the existing
position, but to seek to change the 1977 European Community directive on
employees' acquired rights.
The government insists that 'as a general rule' regulations on undertakings
do not apply to local authorities in spite of recent court decisions. It
believes that new employers do not inherit the terms and conditions of
employees who used to do the job for the local authority. However, several
local authorities have been given conflicting legal advice and believe that
new contracts must respect former employees' rights.
Oswestry district council, in Shropshire, is about to take the government to
court on the issue. It is challenging an Environment Department instruction
that it should put its refuse collection out to tender again because it
included a transfer of undertakings clause in its original contract.
Dyfed county council, in south-west Wales, was last night faced with
reinstating 950 staff it made redundant last month following a dispute over
transfer of undertakings.
Council challenge, Page 8
</TEXT>
