<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / BP to cut workforce by 20,500 worldwide
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES and PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Petroleum yesterday announced it would cut a further 9,000 jobs
worldwide by 1995, increasing an earlier figure for expected job losses to a
total of 20,500, or 20 per cent of the workforce.
The cuts are in addition to previously announced plans to cut 11,500 jobs by
early 1993.
The job losses are part of a cost-cutting drive launched by Mr David Simon
when he became group chief executive. this year. BP aims to cut Dollars 1bn
(Pounds 600m) from operating costs by 1995.
The company said yesterday it had set a target to make 5,000 direct job cuts
over the next two years, with a further 4,000 jobs to be lost through the
divestment of peripheral businesses.
The latest reductions will come mainly from the downstream part of the
business - refining operations and petrol stations - where competition and
low oil products prices have squeezed margins while demand remains affected
by the recession. But BP also indicated that further cuts in its corporate
staff will be made.
BP has suffered from increasing debts and a huge net cash outflow to fund
its ambitious oil exploration programme.
The company is expected to incur a loss of around Pounds 500m this year on a
replacement cost basis, partly as a result of provisions made for job cuts
mid-year.
The company's debt-to-equity ratio is at 87 per cent and, in spite of the
dividend cut earlier this year, analysts believe it could rise above 90 per
cent by the end of the year.
But Mr Simon hopes that by saving Dollars 1bn a year, he can add Dollars
600m to annual profits by 1995.
He hopes to cut Dollars 400m from refining and marketing costs, Dollars 300m
from the corporate centre, Dollars 200m from exploration and production and
Dollars 100m from chemicals.
He also hopes to boost profits by a further Dollars 400m from reduced
advance corporation tax tax payments and improved efficiency.
BP Chemicals yesterday said it was closing a 50,000 tonne a year butadiene
plant with the loss of 40 jobs at its Baglan Bay site in South Wales, adds
Paul Abrahams. Dow Chemical announced yesterday it was mothballing a 20,000
tonne a year polystyrene plant in Bilbao and shutting a 14,000 tonne a year
latex unit from May.
London Stock Exchange, Page 40
