<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / Red tape relaxed for EC trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CUSTOMS &amp; Excise department will shortly issue details of simplified
administrative arrangements for businesses trading with other EC countries.
The guidance follows successful negotiations to reduce red tape associated
with 'triangulation' - where goods or payments between a supplier in one EC
country and a customer in another pass through an agent in a third.
Under initial EC proposals, that agent would have had to be registered for
VAT, account for tax and submit detailed statistical documents in every
country with which it did business.
But EC member states' finance ministers agreed in a meeting this week to the
wording of a simplified directive that will reduce the burdens on business.
UK Customs officials described the previous arrangements as a 'running
sore', which had generated considerable anguish and complaints from British
business.
Under the new arrangements, the final customer for the goods will account
for any tax paid, while the intermediate agent will simply complete a
regular form called the EC sales list.
</TEXT>
