<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: Caution on Bosnia reflects risks of
entanglement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR'S cautious response yesterday to calls for military
enforcement of the United Nations no-fly zone over war-torn Bosnia reflects
growing concern at the risks of an ever more dangerous military
entanglement.
As international momentum builds for much tougher action against Serbian
forces, senior ministers are engaged in an intense debate about the
political and military risks facing the government.
Some of Mr Major's colleagues - notably Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign
secretary - are concerned that without further restraint Serbia will become
increasingly confident in its dismissal of international pressure.
Mr Hurd's assessment is that the combination of sanctions and public
opprobrium so far has done little to curb the Serbs' territorial ambitions.
The end result might be the spread of the present conflict in Bosnia to
Macedonia and Kosovo, in turn sparking a full-scale war in the Balkans.
His fears are shared by many ministerial colleagues. Yet there is a
substantial voice in the cabinet arguing also that Britain cannot run the
risk to the lives of 2,400 British troops that would result from a decision
by the UN to shoot down Serbian aircraft in the no-fly zone.
As one minister put it: 'American planes can safely shoot down Serbian
helicopters. They could not prevent the Serbs from retaliating against our
ground forces.'
Mr Malcolm Rikfind, the defence secretary, has warned repeatedly of the risk
of heavy casualties.
The most cautious in the cabinet argue also that there is no political
pressure on the government to risk the lives of British troops.
Although public opinion may be outraged by the barbaric behaviour of Serbian
forces, it shares the fears of the government about deeper military
involvement.
Such tension was evident in Mr Major's response to MPs when he was pressed
by Mr John Smith to join the US and France in pressing for a new UN
resolution to allow the use of military force to halt Serbian flights.
Mr Major - who will discuss the crisis in weekend talks in Washington with
President George Bush - was careful not to dismiss the possibility of a new
UN resolution.
His officials regard it as inevitable.
But by emphasising the risks - both to the UN humanitarian effort and to the
lives of British troops - he underlined that Britain favoured a steady
ratcheting upwards in the pressure on Serbia rather than an immediate
'shoot-to-kill' policy against Serbian aircraft.
The prime minister will also suggest to President Bush alternative ways to
intensify pressure on the Serbs.
Whitehall officials have been drawing up plans to intensify sanctions -
possibly including the breaking of telecommunications links and the
derecognition of all Serbian diplomats.
More controversially, officials have also been examining the possibility of
suggesting an end of the blanket UN embargo on arms shipments to the region.
Some ministers believe there is a strong moral case to break from
traditional international practice and agree to arm the Bosnians, whose
equipment is far inferior to that of the Serbs.
Even those measures would carry risks. The humanitarian convoys in Bosnia
depend on Serbian acquiescence. Were its enemies to be better armed, Serbia
might well withdraw such co-operation, attack British troops and pour more
of its own regular forces into Bosnia. Against that background, it is easy
to understand Mr Major's caution.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
