<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / Parliament and Politics: PM upbeat on outlook for economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A revival of business confidence in 1993 was forecast by Mr John Major, the
prime minister, yesterday in his final question time appearance in the
Commons before the Christmas recess.
He told MPs that Britain had a 'very solid platform' for industrial
recovery.
Tory backbenchers were clearly heartened by his firm endorsement of the
optimism expressed by Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, on Monday about the
prospects for the economy.
The prime minister backed the view of Mr Peter Butler (C Milton Keynes North
East) that there were already signs of a 'fully justified growth in business
confidence' throughout the country by adding: 'You will see a good deal more
of that in the months to come.'
Brushing aside sceptical comments from the Labour benches, he emphasised
that in addition to Britain's annual rate of inflation falling to 3 per
cent, 'factory gate inflation' was down to the lowest level for a
generation.
Mr Major said it was the clearest sign yet that the battle against inflation
 -so vital for industry, commerce, investment and jobs - was being won.
To Tory cheers, he insisted: 'It is precisely because of this success that
we now have the lowest interest rates in the European Community, and a very
solid platform for industrial recovery next year.'
Responding to further plaudits from Tory loyalists for his handling of last
weekend's summit in Edinburgh, the prime minister said it would become
increasingly apparent that Britain had set the agenda for the entire EC.
He underlined the 'significant turnround' in the attitude of some member
states to the enlargement of the EC.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
