<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / Carlton warns on Channel 5 deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CARLTON TELEVISION has warned the Independent Television Commission that it
may seek a judicial review if the Channel 5 franchise is awarded to Channel
Five Holdings, the consortium led by Thames Television.
The commission is due to decide tomorrow whether to award the franchise  -
which will cover about 70 per cent of the UK population - to the Thames
consortium, the only bidder.
If the commission decided not to award the franchise, it might face a
judicial review threat from Thames. Carlton, which will take over the London
weekday franchise from Thames on New Year's day, is concerned that it might
face competition from Channel 5 in London before the end of its first year
on air.
At issue is likely to be the nature of the proposed service from the
consortium. Carlton will argue that the 1990 Broadcasting Act envisaged a
national channel with the obligation to show a diversity of programmes and
not a London-based service to be shown all over the country. At a later
date, Channel 5 plans to provide services from other cities such as
Manchester, Birmingham and Glasgow, although it may be the turn of the
century before those are established.
The consortium's programme plans reflect the focus of one of its important
backers: Mr Moses Znaimer, founder of CityTV in Toronto, which specialises
in local news, films and popular music.
The ITC has to decide whether the consortium's finances and programme plans
pass a quality threshold. It must also be certain that the consortium can
retune millions of video recorders likely to suffer interference from the
Channel 5 signal. Apart from Thames and its parent, Thorn EMI, Channel Five
Holdings has the backing of Time Warner, the world's biggest media company.
Associated Newspapers; Pearson, owner of the Financial Times; and Cox, the
Atlanta-based media group, are among those which told the commission they
are interested in investing in the project.
Thames has made the minimum bid of Pounds 1,000 a year and, unlike all but
the smallest ITV companies, Channel 5 will not have to pay part of its
advertising revenue to the government.
UK Gold funding, Page 24
</TEXT>
