<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / Advert 'untruths' are attacked
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GARY MEAD, Marketing Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Advertising Standards Authority has accused estate agents and property
developers of using 'blatant untruths' and 'hidden conditions' in
advertising intended to tempt customers in a collapsed market.
In its latest monthly report, the authority quotes a housebuilder claiming
that a development was in quiet countryside when it was next to a busy
military airbase.
The authority said some estate agents were using misleading illustrations of
property. 'Advertisers have been known to feature houses unbeknown to their
owners,' it explained.
The report covers complaints about advertising against more than 100
companies. Among those rejected by the authority, an independent
self-regulatory body, was one filed against Co-operative Bank by the
Cosmetic Toiletry and Perfumery Association. It objected to some of the
bank's advertisements that were critical of cosmetic testing on animals and
were used by the bank to promote its investment policies.
The authority upheld one complaint against a British Airways newspaper
advertisement which promoted a 'return ticket to the USA from Pounds 309',
but failed to mention that the offer required a minimum one-week stay.
Forte Hotels was found to have misled customers through an advertisement
promoting a special offer of a three-night break for Pounds 113, which
included a table d'hote menu.
The complainant discovered that no such menu had been on offer at any of the
hotels in the chain for the previous 12 months.
</TEXT>
