<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / Road cash rules will change
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RULES ON allocating money for local road and transport schemes in England
will be changed to enable councils to submit joint bids for big projects, Mr
John MacGregor, the transport secretary, said yesterday.
The move follows an agreed approach in deciding transport priorities for
next year from seven local authorities in the west Midlands.
Two of the authorities' top four priorities - but not the Midland Metro -
will go ahead next year.
Mr MacGregor told MPs he would start consulting local-authority associations
about bringing in the new arrangements in time for spending bids in 1994-95.
They are intended to allow some flexibility between the local grant
allocated for capital spending on roads and that for public transport. The
flexibility will be confined to less than half of the transport grant in the
first year, not least because of restrictions in the legislation.
The chance to submit joint bids is most likely to be taken up in areas where
more than one authority is involved, such as Tyneside. County councils'
priorities as highway authorities tend to remain within their own
boundaries.
The announcement came as Mr MacGregor gave details of how the Pounds 1.047bn
for capital spending on local roads in 1993-94 would be spent. Some Pounds
473m is already earmarked for existing commitments, but 41 significant
schemes will be started at a cost of Pounds 93m. Bridge works and structural
maintenance on main roads account for a further Pounds 310m.
Among the largest schemes to proceed is the Blackwater Valley route in
Hampshire and Surrey, costing Pounds 57m.
Mr MacGregor said the settlement 'demonstrates the government's priority of
maintaining strong capital investment' and emphasised the help it would
bring to the construction industry.
Mr John Prescott, the shadow transport secretary, welcomed the move to allow
joint bids from local authorities. The British Roads Federation said that
the government was contributing directly only Pounds 440m in grant, and that
local authorities would have to find more than Pounds 600m from their own
resources or from borrowing if the programme was to be realised.
</TEXT>
