<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / Council challenges government on contracting out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ONE OF England's smallest local authorities is seeking judicial review of a
government order requiring it to put its refuse collection contract out to
tender for a second time.
After a complaint from a company wishing to bid, the Environment Department
instructed Oswestry Council in Shropshire to re-tender. It said, the council
had wrongly included a clause in the tender binding contractors to maintain
the 17 employees' terms and conditions.
Mr Brian Catton, Oswestry's deputy chief executive and solicitor, said: 'I
believe we had to do so because of doubt over whether or not the 1981
transfer-of-undertakings regulations apply. If the regulations apply, then
any redundancy payments we made would have been ultra vires.
'I've had no end of inquiries from local authorities up and down the country
about our position.'
The troubles afflicting Oswestry - combined with further difficulties for
Dyfed County Council in Wales - highlight the growing confusion over whether
employees' terms and conditions must be respected when services are put out
to compulsory competitive tendering.
Oswestry's decision to challenge the government is based on advice that the
1981 regulations enshrining the European Community's 1977 Acquired Rights
Directive in British law may apply to councils. That would make them
vulnerable to legal action, particularly from employees made redundant as a
result of a contract going outside.
Dyfed last month awarded its cleaning contract to Initial Cleaning Services
and Office Cleaning Services. The contracts were due to start on New Year's
day.
When Dyfed issued redundancy notices to its 950 cleaners, Nupe, their union,
launched industrial tribunal proceedings on grounds of unfair dismissal.
That was based on the council's failure to provide information as required
under the 1981 regulations.
Acting on counsel's advice, Mr David Irving, the county secretary and
solicitor, put the contractors 'on notice' about the Nupe claims. Both
companies, acting on their own advice, said they believed the regulations
did not apply, but asked the county council to indemnify them in case they
did.
'We could not possibly write that kind of blank cheque, so had to withdraw
the contract,' Mr Irving said.
Dyfed now plans to reinstate the cleaners, and re-tender its contract with a
transfer-of-undertakings clause - making it liable to government action
similar to that meted out to Oswestry.
At least one of the contractors is considering taking Dyfed to court.
Ms Libby Glare-Williams, Initial Cleaning Services' company secretary, said
yesterday: 'We will have to take decisions on a case-by-case basis in the
future. We work on close margins and do not price on the basis of
undertakings being transferred. Nobody is quite sure what the position is at
the moment.'
Mr Roy Williams, assistant secretary at the Association of County Councils,
said local-authority associations were seeking a 'clear legal ruling' on the
position. 'Our view is that local authorities should be free to take
decisions without fear of action as in the case of Oswestry.'
The dispute will move to the Commons next month, when MPs will debate clause
26 of the Employment Bill. Companies and council associations say the
clause, which removes the exemption of undertakings 'not in the nature of a
commercial venture' from the 1981 regulations, will confuse the position
further.
The government says 'as a general rule' competitive tendering should be
unaffected by either clause 26 or recent court cases.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
</DOC>
