<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / Manufacturing output increases 0.3% in October
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   A SMALL rise in manufacturing output in October
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
0.3 per cent - was fuelled by buoyant growth in chemicals and electrical
engineering.
The boost to chemicals came mainly from strong export growth, while output
was higher across the electrical engineering sector.
This was the first rise in manufacturing output since June, although output
has maintained roughly the same levels since the beginning of the year. The
latest official figures confirm that overall factory production remains
flat.
In the three months to the end of the October - a period the Central
Statistical Office says is a better measure of manufacturing trends - output
fell by a seasonally adjusted 0.2 per cent, and was 0.1 per cent lower
compared with the corresponding three months a year ago.
The biggest falls over the three months to October occurred in the metals
sector, where a sharp drop in steel production caused the output of metal
goods to fall 0.6 per cent compared with the previous month, and 2.5 per
cent compared with a year ago.
That was offset by robust car production. The sector enjoyed strong exports
in October for the second month running and almost maintained the level of
output achieved in September after August's very sharp fall.
In the three months to the end of October, output was 2.4 per cent lower
compared with the previous three months, but 5.4 per cent higher than the
same period a year ago.
Food, drink and tobacco production dropped 4.7 per cent over the three
months to October compared with the previous three months. That followed
exceptionally high output in May and June, when warm weather boosted sales
of soft drinks and beer. Output in the remaining manufacturing sectors was
flat.
Clothing and footwear production was at the same level between August and
October. The output of paper, printing and publishing has been unchanged
since June.
The 1.2 per cent rise in industrial output - which includes the output of
energy industries - was due to higher energy production. Oil and gas
extraction in the three months to the end of October was 8.6 per cent higher
than in the previous three months, mainly reflecting the very cold weather
in that month, one of the coldest Octobers on record. Other energy and water
supply output rose by 3 per cent over the same period.
PM upbeat, Page 10
