<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / Lawyers seek to avert legal aid cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BARRISTERS and solicitors in England and Wales offered yesterday to accept a
legal-aid pay freeze next year if the government withdrew proposals outlined
in the Autumn Statement to cut legal-aid eligibility.
The offer was made by the Law Society, the Bar and the Legal Aid
Practitioner's Group in response to indications from Lord Mackay, the Lord
Chancellor, earlier this month that he would welcome 'suggestions on how the
legal-aid budget might be contained otherwise than I proposed'.
Lord Mackay's plans, including a reduced level of disposable income that
applicants can earn before being entitled to free legal aid, were attacked
by lawyers and consumer organisations as a severe limitation on access to
justice.
The Law Society estimates that 10m people will become ineligible for civil
legal aid.
Lord Taylor, the Lord Chief Justice, giving this year's Richard Dimbleby
lecture recently, said falling eligibility was a 'blot' on the justice
system.
The society, in a letter to Lord Mackay, called on the government to
withdraw the proposed cuts in eligibility and start urgent discussions on
substitute measures.
Lawyers believe ways can be found to contain costs within public-expenditure
targets that will be less damaging to the public.
The offer to freeze legal-aid pay is unlikely to be popular with grassroots
legal-aid lawyers who have complained loudly in recent years about erosion
of legal-aid fees in real terms.
Legal-aid pay rates are reviewed each April. This year lawyers received a 3
per cent increase in fees. The society said with rapidly rising overheads
that amounted to a pay cut of 5 per cent in real terms.
</TEXT>
