<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / Shoppers delay Christmas spree
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSUMERS APPEAR to be saving their Christmas shopping for the days
immediately before the holiday, a survey from the Confederation of British
Industry indicated yesterday.
The CBI's latest distributive trades survey, published yesterday, pointed to
a fall in retail sales volumes in November compared with the previous year.
However, a significant divergence emerged between large and small retailers.
While a majority of bigger retailers said business increased compared with
November 1991, a majority of smaller shops reported a decline. Mr Nigel
Whittaker, chairman of the CBI's distributive trades panel, said the wet
weather in November 'probably acted as a dampener on discretionary sales'.
Sales volumes for grocers, chemists, footwear and leather, furniture and
carpet stores were higher than in November last year. But durable household
goods, clothing, hardware, china and do-it-yourself stores, along with
off-licences, booksellers and stationers reported that business was down on
an annual basis.
'November continued to reveal mixed fortunes for retailers,' Mr Nigel
Whittaker said.
He said retailers expected business volumes to be virtually unchanged this
month from last year's levels. It was very difficult to predict the
Christmas trade, though. 'Every year people leave their Christmas shopping
later and later,' he said. 'There is everything to go for.'
The CBI's latest survey of companies in the retail, wholesale and motor
trades indicates that there will be further job losses and investment cuts
in the distributive trades over the next three months. On the other hand,
the outlook is favourable for consumers, with retailers reporting annual
price increases that are among the lowest since the CBI survey began in
1983.
Recent CBI surveys have been less optimistic about retail sales than
government figures, which have shown a modest underlying increase.
Mr Whittaker said yesterday that discrepancy, with weak consumer confidence
figures, justified caution about the outlook for consumer spending.
'However, with bank base rates at 7 per cent, the conditions appear to be in
place for a modest upturn in consumer demand in the new year,' he said.
The CBI survey showed that retailers hesitated to place orders with their
suppliers. Across the distributive trades as a whole, import penetration
fell because of a reduction of buying abroad by the wholesale and motor
trades. By contrast, retailers' deliveries covered by imports rose slightly
compared with a year ago.
Mr Whittaker said: 'Investment plans among retailers, wholesalers and motor
traders continue to deteriorate as business confidence weakens further. The
sharp job losses reported and expected across the distributive trades
reflect companies' determination to cut costs.'
The survey was conducted between November 17 and December 2. The 483
respondents cover 15,000 outlets in retailing, wholesaling and the motor
trades.
