<HEADLINE>
FT  16 DEC 92 / IDA plans to target poorest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERNE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE International Development Association (IDA), provider of low-cost aid to
developing countries, said yesterday it would distribute more of its
resources to the world's poorest, least creditworthy countries, Reuter
reports from Berne.
The IDA, an arm of the World Bank, also said its 34 donor countries had
agreed to replenish IDA funds with SDR13bn (Pounds 11.8bn) over three years
from next July.
The IDA 'will reduce the share of its lending to countries able to access
international financial markets as well as IDA resources,' said Mr Ernest
Stern, World Bank managing director.
The countries likely to receive less of IDA's aid than in previous years
were China, India, Pakistan, and Nigeria.
The 34 donor countries met in Berne to complete the negotiations on the 10th
replenishment of IDA resources.
In Washington, Mr Lewis Preston, the World Bank's president, said in a
speech to the World Resources Institute, a Washington-based research group,
that his organisation's efforts to tackle other developmental and
environmental problems depended on its success in reducing poverty.
Mr Preston called on industrialised nations to help developing countries
attack the problems of unclean water, inadequate sanitation, soil
degradation and population control.
</TEXT>
